  "prompt": "I was wondering, is money laundering against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is against the law in virtually every country around the world. It is a criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the funds appear as though they come from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**, the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, and other federal laws. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and significant prison time.\n\nInternationally, efforts to combat money laundering are coordinated by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CFT). Many countries have enacted laws and regulations to align with these standards.\n\nIf you have specific questions or concerns about this topic, it\u2019s always a good idea to consult a legal professional.",
